{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"1c05a347-97b9-4546-ab84-9bf172323e7a","content":"Yes, both are known MSTest v4 breaking changes. Here's what's happening:\n\n### 1. Lost test history in Azure DevOps\nMSTest v4 changed the **fully qualified test ID format**. Azure DevOps matches history by test ID, so all tests appear new. This is cosmetic — history will rebuild over time.\n\n### 2. `TestContext.TestName` in `[ClassInitialize]`\nIn v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` is a **class-level context** — it's not associated with any individual test. Accessing `TestName` now throws `InvalidOperationException`. In v3 it silently returned the name of whichever test triggered initialization first (which was unreliable anyway).\n\n**Fix for your code** — remove the `TestName` access from `ClassInit`:","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_0158sgNaJ3U1Wfagz6Wgp6vD","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"/tmp/sv-eef72f843be84c029127d5be4e3502d0/SetupTests.cs","old_str":"    [ClassInitialize]\n    public static void ClassInit(TestContext context)\n    {\n        var testName = context.TestName;\n        // Log setup for specific test\n    }","new_str":"    [ClassInitialize]\n    public static void ClassInit(TestContext context)\n    {\n        // In MSTest v4, TestContext in [ClassInitialize] is class-scoped;\n        // TestName is only available in [TestInitialize] or test methods.\n    }"},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"edit the file at /tmp/sv-eef72f843be84c029127d5be4e3502d0/SetupTests.cs."}],"interactionId":"8bf76173-3d27-4e06-91ee-0e93499bfa2c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about MSTest v4 breaking changes. Let me provide a comprehensive answer based on my knowledge of MSTest v4 changes.\n\nKey MSTest v4 breaking changes:\n\n1. **Fully Qualified Test Names changed** — MSTest v4 changed how test IDs are computed (the fully qualified name format). This is why Azure DevOps sees them as \"new\" tests with no history. The test ID is now based on the namespace + class + method, but the format changed.\n\n2. **TestContext.TestName in [ClassInitialize]** — In MSTest v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` is a class-level context, not tied to any specific test. So accessing `TestContext.TestName` throws an `InvalidOperationException` because there is no \"current test\" during class initialization. In v3, this used to return the name of the first test that triggered the class initialization.\n   \n3. There are several other breaking changes worth noting: `[ClassInitialize]` and `[ClassCleanup]` now require explicit `InheritanceBehavior.BeforeEachDerivedClass` to run for derived classes, `TestContext` is injected through the constructor rather than set via property, `DeploymentItem` behavior has changed, `DataRow` attributes handle complex types differently, and some assertions have stricter validation. The issue on line 13 is specifically that accessing `context.TestName` inside `[ClassInitialize]` will fail because there's no active test context at that point.","outputTokens":821,"requestId":"CFC9:1FFE72:6677AA9:72A54C9:69EC2B78"},"id":"e99b60b3-fce8-4411-a7ce-9e94f4cbab3f","timestamp":"2026-04-25T02:48:41.745Z","parentId":"61f7c55a-9735-4f93-85df-d821675a0c83"}
